scenarioDescription:
The HATS-33 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HATS-33 is a star with 1.06 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.02 times its radius. It is located 831.70 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 3 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HATS-33 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HATS-33 system


HATS-33 b

HATS-33 b was discovered by the HATSouth observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.04 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HATS-33 b is 379.056 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HATS-33 b is 13.787 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HATS-33 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
description: 3D visualisation and gravity simulation of the exoplanet system HATS-33, which contains 1 planets and was discovered by HATSouth.
